commit f6e72df55f444b7ba57e7965d190c5e9630ea14c
Author: Dmitry Antipov <dmantipov@yandex.ru>

modules: extend {kstrdup,kfree}_const() to handle per-module .rodata

This commit extends kstrdup_const() and kfree_const() to handle module
.rodata sections. It aims to avoid unnecessary string copying for constants
defined within kernel modules.

> diff --git a/kernel/module/main.c b/kernel/module/main.c
> index c3ce106c70af..5003cacd0786 100644
> --- a/kernel/module/main.c
> +++ b/kernel/module/main.c
[ ... ]
> @@ -3858,6 +3858,15 @@ bool is_module_text_address(unsigned long addr)
>  	return __module_text_address(addr) != NULL;
>  }
>  
> +bool is_module_rodata(unsigned long addr)
> +{
> +	struct module *mod;
> +
> +	guard(rcu)();
> +	mod = __module_address(addr);

During module unload, delete_module() sets the module state to
MODULE_STATE_UNFORMED. If a deferred free runs concurrently and calls
kfree_const(), is_module_rodata() will call __module_address().

Looking at __module_address(), it returns NULL if the state is
MODULE_STATE_UNFORMED:

kernel/module/main.c:__module_address() {
        ...
        if (mod) {
                BUG_ON(!within_module(addr, mod));
                if (mod->state == MODULE_STATE_UNFORMED)
                        mod = NULL;
        }
        return mod;
}

Will this cause is_module_rodata() to return false during the unload window,
resulting in kfree_const() incorrectly passing the module .rodata pointer
to kfree() and crashing the slab allocator?

> +	return mod && within_module_mem_type(addr, mod, MOD_RODATA);
> +}
> +
> diff --git a/mm/util.c b/mm/util.c
> index f063fd4de1e8..b152ab489e9b 100644
> --- a/mm/util.c
> +++ b/mm/util.c
[ ... ]
> @@ -42,7 +43,8 @@
>   */
>  void kfree_const(const void *x)
>  {
> -	if (!is_kernel_rodata((unsigned long)x))
> +	if (!is_kernel_rodata((unsigned long)x) &&
> +	    !is_module_rodata((unsigned long)x))
>  		kfree(x);
>  }

If a kernel object (like a kobject or kernfs_node) is initialized with a
string from a module's .rodata using kstrdup_const(), what happens if the
object outlives the module?

For example, if user-space holds a sysfs file open while the module is
unloaded, the object will be destroyed after the module memory is freed.
Since the module is gone, is_module_rodata() will return false, causing
kfree_const() to pass the dangling pointer to kfree(). Can this crash the
slab allocator?

[ ... ]
> @@ -98,7 +100,8 @@ EXPORT_SYMBOL(kstrdup);
>   */
>  const char *kstrdup_const(const char *s, gfp_t gfp)
>  {
> -	if (is_kernel_rodata((unsigned long)s))
> +	if (is_kernel_rodata((unsigned long)s) ||
> +	    is_module_rodata((unsigned long)s))
>  		return s;
>  
>  	return kstrdup(s, gfp);

There are several places in the kernel that manually check
!is_kernel_rodata() before freeing a string.

For example, in fs/kernfs/dir.c:kernfs_rename_ns():

        if (new_name && !is_kernel_rodata((unsigned long)old_name))
                kfree_rcu_mightsleep(old_name);

Since this patch allows kstrdup_const() to return module .rodata pointers,
won't these manual checks evaluate to true for module strings and pass the
module address directly to kfree_rcu_mightsleep() or kfree()?

